title Pool confirmed; Quin proposed as the Q-vane of the four voices; the sandbox loop composed not newly-named
prompt Keaton confirmed Pool and asked to continue; proposed Quin as the Q-vane — a unifying vane for the four voices (Lantern/Lattice/Anvil/Scribble) under Glow TAME + Maze guidance; and asked where to seed nested deterministic testing for agents-spawning-agents in sandboxes (under Neth, Pond, Quin, or another vane), where testing is part of the prompting — Glow vibe-coding automation, TAME/Maze guided.
think Seated Pool as confirmed across names-awaiting-confirmation, LEXICON, TASKS, and the Pool design doc's open questions (its remaining questions are now build questions — whole-vane-vs-market-specialized, seat-now-vs-defer — not name gates).
think Searched Quin before endorsing, as with every vane name: zero "quin" in the Urbit kernel (Arvo/Zuse/Hoon/Lull/all vanes). The only occurrences are "quintillion"/"quindecillion" inside number-to-words.hoon — incidental English number words, not a term. So Quin is a free, additive Q-vane name (after Pool's P), nothing to rename.
think Framed Quin as the same good move Pool made: a named host for real, scattered, already-working pieces. The inference family (Lattice arithmetic, Scribble reading, Lantern asking, Anvil forge) is four peer modules with no vane; Quin gathers them as the four voices of one instrument under TAME (bounds + witnesses applied once at the vane) and Maze shelter (the nursery is exactly for a proposal gathering working pieces while it earns its single responsibility). The name teaches its function — quin as the fifth thing the four voices make, and the count fits (vane + four voices = five).
think Gave the honest answer to the sandbox question rather than pick one vane: it is not one home but a composition each vane already owns. Neth owns the seeded deterministic replay (the testing engine, from the IronBeetle silo); Puddle owns the ephemeral isolated regions (Pond bounds inside); Quin (or Pool) owns the agents. So the sandbox loop = Quin (agents/Glow vibe-coding) × Puddle (ephemeral snapshot-able region, own Kumara/policy) × Neth (byte-for-byte replay), Maze-sheltered, TAME-guided (bounded sandbox, asserted test, pinned result never predicted). Recommended composing rather than naming a new vane — the same invent-no-primitive instinct that shaped Pool; if a single named pattern is wanted it belongs in the Maze nursery, not as a canonical vane.
obs Two proposals, one verdict each: Quin is worth confirming (free name, real unification, Maze-right); the sandbox loop is worth building as a composition, not naming — seeding it "under Neth" is half-right (replay engine) and "under Pond" is half-right (isolation), and the whole is Quin × Puddle × Neth. Naming a fresh vane for it would repeat the junk-drawer risk Maze exists to prevent.
